          "body": "Paul names the *cause* of the Corinthian heart-restriction: their refusal to disentangle from pagan alliances. *Do not be bound together with unbelievers* (v.14) — the verb *heterozugeo* is drawn from Deuteronomy 22:10’s prohibition on yoking ox and donkey, mismatched animals that cannot plow together. Paul then presses with five rhetorical questions, each demanding the answer *none*: righteousness/lawlessness, light/darkness, Christ/Belial, believer/unbeliever, temple/idols. The vocabulary climbs in intensity — *metoche* (sharing), *koinonia* (fellowship), *sumphonesis* (symphony — even harmonic agreement), *meris* (portion), *sugkatathesis* (consent). Five different words for *partnership* annihilated by five categorical antitheses. The naming of *Belial* (v.15) — Hebrew *beliyaʿal*, worthlessness, by Second Temple usage a personal name for Satan (cf. Jubilees 1:20; 1QM 13) — reframes the question cosmically: the alliance is not merely with unbelievers but with the kingdom they unwittingly serve."
