      {
        "number": 4,
        "title": "The five incompatibilities — no shared yoke",
        "range": "6:14-16a",
        "excerpt": "Do not be bound together with unbelievers; for what partnership have righteousness and lawlessness, or what fellowship has light with darkness?",
        "body": "The central command of the chapter’s second half is one prohibition: *me ginesthe heterozugountes apistois* — *do not become unequally yoked with unbelievers*. The verb *heterozugeo* is rare and likely Paul’s coinage; the cognate adjective in Leviticus 19:19 LXX prohibits crossbreeding livestock, and Deuteronomy 22:10 prohibits yoking an ox and a donkey together. Paul draws the prohibition from purity-of-yoke laws to address a wider issue: any binding partnership across the believer/unbeliever divide that compromises the believer’s ability to walk the gospel.\n\nThe specific applications are debated. Marriage is included (cf. 1 Corinthians 7:39 — *only in the Lord*), but Paul’s scope is broader. Calvin reads it as covering close associations of every kind that involve shared moral and religious life. Charles Hodge and Murray Harris emphasize the Corinthian setting: trade-guild banquets, civic festivals tied to pagan worship, business partnerships that required participation in idolatrous oath-rituals. The principle is not avoidance of unbelievers in commerce or society (cf. 1 Corinthians 5:9-10) but refusal of binding alliances that yoke the believer to the moral and religious life of paganism. Today the principle reaches into marriage, business partnerships, deep mentorship relationships, theological co-belligerence with movements whose foundational allegiances differ, and any covenantal binding that asks the believer to function as though the Lordship of Christ were optional.\n\nPaul then presses with five rhetorical questions in vv.14-16a, each demanding the answer *none*. The vocabulary climbs deliberately: *metoche* (partnership) → *koinonia* (fellowship) → *sumphonesis* (symphony) → *meris* (portion) → *sugkatathesis* (agreement). Five different words for shared life, each annihilated by a categorical pairing: righteousness with lawlessness, light with darkness, Christ with Belial, believer with unbeliever, temple of God with idols.\n\nThe naming of Belial (v.15) deserves attention. In Hebrew *beliyaʿal* means *worthlessness*; in the LXX it appears in 1 Samuel 1:16 and elsewhere as a noun for wickedness. By the Second Temple period (Jubilees 1:20; 1QM — the War Scroll from Qumran; Testament of the Twelve Patriarchs) *Belial* had become a personal name for Satan or the principal demonic adversary. Paul’s use of it here — the only NT occurrence — reframes the question cosmically. The pagan alliances are not merely with people who happen to disagree; they are with a kingdom whose head is the personal enemy of Christ.\n\nThe argument is not that believers must avoid all contact with unbelievers — Paul has already corrected that misreading in 1 Corinthians 5:9-10. The argument is that no binding partnership can erase the categorical difference between two communities whose foundational allegiances are mutually exclusive. Light and darkness can share a room; they cannot share a nature.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Heterozugeo* (v.14) — *hetero* (different-kind) + *zugos* (yoke); the cognate is in Leviticus 19:19 LXX. *Belial* (v.15) is the only NT occurrence; the LXX more commonly transliterates it as *beliar*. *Sumphonesis* (v.15) — the noun behind English *symphony* — picks up musical-harmonic agreement, suggesting that Christ and Belial cannot even play in the same key."
      },
      {
        "number": 5,
        "title": "The temple identity and the OT chain quotation",
        "range": "6:16b-18",
        "excerpt": "For we are the temple of the living God… “I will be a father to you, and you shall be sons and daughters to Me,” Says the Lord Almighty.",
        "body": "The ground of the separation is the chapter’s most decisive identity statement: *hemeis gar naos theou esmen zontos* — *for we are the temple of the living God*. *Naos*, not *hieron* — the inner sanctuary, the Holy of Holies, the place of YHWH’s manifest presence — not the outer temple precincts. Paul applies this most-sacred category to the corporate church (the *we* is plural, echoing 1 Corinthians 3:16-17 where the same point is made of the local congregation). The temple metaphor is not decorative; it is the theological reason cohabitation with idols is impossible. A temple by definition hosts one deity. To host another is not to expand worship but to defile the sanctuary.\n\nPaul then issues a chain quotation of four OT texts, weaving them into one continuous divine speech. (1) *I will dwell in them and walk among them; and I will be their God, and they shall be My people* — drawn from Leviticus 26:12 with influence from Ezekiel 37:27. The Levitical promise stands at the heart of the Sinai covenant; Ezekiel applies it to the eschatological restoration. Paul reads both as fulfilled in the church. (2) *Therefore come out from their midst and be separate, says the Lord; and do not touch what is unclean* — Isaiah 52:11, originally addressed to the exiles being called out of Babylon with the temple vessels. The geographic exile of Israel becomes the spiritual separation of the church from pagan alliances. (3) *And I will welcome you* — likely from Ezekiel 20:34, where God promises to gather the dispersed. The pattern is consistent: separation is the condition; welcome is the divine response.\n\nThe climactic quotation (v.18) takes 2 Samuel 7:14 — God’s dynastic promise to David through Nathan — and expands it. Where the original said *I will be a father to him, and he shall be a son to Me* (singular, of David’s seed), Paul renders it *I will be a father to you* (plural — to the whole church) *and you shall be sons and daughters to Me*. The addition of *daughters* (likely drawing on Isaiah 43:6) democratizes the Davidic adoption promise across gender. Every believer in the Corinthian church — male and female — stands in the position originally granted to David’s royal heir. The chapter’s climax is therefore not the demand for separation but the *consequence* of obedient separation: full covenant family with the God of David.\n\nThe signature is striking. *Says the Lord Almighty* — *Kurios Pantokrator* — the LXX rendering of *YHWH Sabaoth* (the LORD of hosts). The title appears only here in the entire Pauline corpus (it dominates Revelation). Paul reaches for the highest divine title in his vocabulary to sign the covenant promise. The same Almighty who commanded Israel’s separation from Babylon and Canaan now commands the Corinthians’ separation from pagan alliances, and stakes His own name on the welcome that follows.\n\nThe practical force is the inverse of how the passage is often heard. Verses 14-18 are not primarily a warning of loss but a promise of inheritance. The believer who refuses the unequal yoke does not lose anything ultimate; he gains what was promised to David. The Corinthian who closes one door opens another that leads to the Father.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Naos* (vv.16, twice) is the inner sanctuary; distinct from *hieron* (temple precincts). The chain quotation in 16-18 weaves Leviticus 26:12, Ezekiel 37:27, Isaiah 52:11, Ezekiel 20:34, 2 Samuel 7:14, and likely Isaiah 43:6 into one divine speech — a Pauline *florilegium* characteristic of Second Temple Jewish exegesis. *Pantokrator* (v.18) translates *YHWH Sabaoth* in the LXX and appears in the NT only here and nine times in Revelation."
      }
